<DOC><DOCNO> AP880513-0039 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0329EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     05-13 0465</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Political Briefs,470</SECOND><HEAD>Ferraro Offers `Hints' to Dukakis, Warning on Bush</HEAD><DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Geraldine Ferraro says she has some``hints'' for Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis on who shouldbe his running mate.   ``If he called me up I might give him a hint or two,'' said theformer congresswoman from Queens, N.Y. and 1984 Democratic vicepresidential candidate.   Ferraro, 52, also issued a warning about Vice President GeorgeBush.   She reminded the 350 people at Thursday's fundraiser for Lt.Gov. Richard A. Licht about Bush's behavior during their 1984debate.   After the contest Bush said he had ``kicked ass.''   ``You remember how George Bush acted that night,'' Ferraro toldthe predominantly female crowd. ``He was so upset. He was seriousone minute and giddy the next ... up down, up down. Talk about moodswings ... you've got to be careful when you put a man in aposition like that.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Iowa Democrats Falling in Line as Race Progresses</HEAD><DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis waspoised to solidify his lead among Democratic activists gatheringSaturday for congressional district conventions.   Dukakis has picked up the endorsement of Iowa DemocraticChairwoman Bonnie Campbell and all five statewide Democraticelected officials, has landed two of the state's nine ``superdelegates'' and is scheduled to collect a third on Monday.   Party leaders predicted he would pick up most of the 34delegates to be picked at the six conventions.   ``I think we're likely to see more movement toward Dukakis,''said Democratic Party spokesman Phil Roeder.   ``Most people now concede that Mike Dukakis is thefront-runner,'' Ms. Campbell said. ``I am expecting he will get thelion's share of the delegates.''   Their comments came on the eve of the district conventions, thethird step in the Democrats' complex method of picking delegatesand hammering out a state platform.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>State Democrats Collect Funds On New Credit Card Purchases</HEAD><DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The state Democratic Party has mailed 65,000applications for Indiana's first political affinity credit card.   The VISA card issued by Indiana National Bank could raise asmuch as $200,000 a year for the state Democratic party, said statechairman John B. Livengood.   The Democratic Party will make a profit off the card by taking acut of the fees, typically 5 percent per purchase charged tomerchants and paid to credit card companies.   The Indiana Democrats will take one-half of 1 percent, saidparty treasurer Larry Cummings.   The card which has a 16.8 percent interest rate and a $3,000credit line, features a silhouette of a bucking donkey, the party'ssymbol.   Republicans in the state had considered the affinity card ideabut dropped it after deciding too many such cards were already onthe market, said party chairman Gordon K. Durnil.</TEXT></DOC>